<h2 id="document-2-psychological-evaluation-report">DOCUMENT 2:
PSYCHOLOGICAL EVALUATION REPORT</h2>
<p><strong>DIAGNOSIS:</strong> Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder,
Combined Presentation <strong>DSM-5 CODE:</strong> 314.01 (F90.2)
<strong>DATE OF DIAGNOSIS:</strong> June 17, 2025</p>
<h3 id="clinical-presentation">CLINICAL PRESENTATION</h3>
<p><strong>CORE SYMPTOMS:</strong> 1. <strong>Inattention:</strong> -
Difficulty sustaining attention in tasks or play activities - Often does
not seem to listen when spoken to directly - Often does not follow
through on instructions and fails to finish tasks - Often has difficulty
organizing tasks and activities - Often avoids, dislikes, or is
reluctant to engage in tasks requiring sustained mental effort - Often
loses things necessary for tasks or activities - Is often easily
distracted by extraneous stimuli - Is often forgetful in daily
activities</p>
<ol start="2" type="1">
<li><strong>Hyperactivity-Impulsivity:</strong>
<ul>
<li>Often fidgets with or taps hands or feet or squirms in seat</li>
<li>Often leaves seat in situations when remaining seated is
expected</li>
<li>Often feels restless</li>
<li>Often unable to play or engage in leisure activities quietly</li>
<li>Is often “on the go,” acting as if “driven by a motor”</li>
<li>Often talks excessively</li>
<li>Often blurts out an answer before a question has been completed</li>
<li>Often has difficulty waiting his/her turn</li>
<li>Often interrupts or intrudes on others</li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>FUNCTIONAL IMPACT:</strong> -
<strong>Academic/Vocational:</strong> Significant impairment in job
performance due to organizational difficulties -
<strong>Social:</strong> Impulsivity affects interpersonal relationships
- <strong>Daily Living:</strong> Forgetfulness and disorganization
impact independent living - <strong>Emotional:</strong> Frustration and
low self-esteem due to functional limitations</p>
<p><strong>COGNITIVE TESTING:</strong> - <strong>Processing
Speed:</strong> Borderline - <strong>Working Memory:</strong> Low
Average - <strong>Verbal Comprehension:</strong> High Average -
<strong>Perceptual Reasoning:</strong> Average</p>
<p><strong>NEUROPSYCHOLOGICAL ASSESSMENT:</strong> - <strong>Continuous
Performance Test (CPT):</strong> - Commission Errors: 15 (Above Average)
- Omission Errors: 12 (Above Average) - Reaction Time Variability: 18
(High) - Attention Scale: 78 (Elevated)</p>
<h2 id="document-3-medical-necessity-for-phenix-navigator">DOCUMENT 3:
MEDICAL NECESSITY FOR PHENIX NAVIGATOR</h2>
<p><strong>CAMDEN BEHAVIORAL WELLNESS</strong> 88 Lindsey Lane, Unit C
St. Marys, GA 31558</p>
<p><strong>DATE:</strong> June 20, 2025 <strong>PATIENT:</strong>
William R. Johnson <strong>DIAGNOSIS:</strong>
Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder</p>
<h3 id="medical-device-requirement">MEDICAL DEVICE REQUIREMENT</h3>
<p>The Phenix Navigator system is medically necessary for Mr. Johnson’s
treatment of ADHD because it provides:</p>
<p><strong>1. Executive Function Compensation:</strong> - Compensates
for working memory deficits - Assists with task initiation and
completion - Provides organizational structure and routines - Supports
planning and time management</p>
<p><strong>2. Attention Support:</strong> - Provides structured
attention training protocols - Assists with focus maintenance - Reduces
distractibility through structured routines - Supports sustained
attention development</p>
<p><strong>3. Impulse Control:</strong> - Provides pause protocols
before decision-making - Assists with emotional regulation - Supports
behavioral inhibition - Reduces impulsive responses</p>
<p><strong>4. Organization and Planning:</strong> - Provides task
management systems - Assists with prioritization - Supports time
management - Reduces forgetfulness through reminders</p>
<p><strong>PROGNOSIS WITH TREATMENT:</strong> With continued use of the
Phenix Navigator system, Mr. Johnson shows significant improvement in: -
Task completion rates - Organizational skills - Time management -
Impulse control - Overall functional independence</p>
<p><strong>PROGNOSIS WITHOUT TREATMENT:</strong> Without the Phenix
Navigator system, Mr. Johnson would experience: - Continued functional
impairment - Increased difficulty with daily tasks - Greater
occupational challenges - Reduced quality of life</p>
<h2 id="document-4-comorbidity-assessment">DOCUMENT 4: COMORBIDITY
ASSESSMENT</h2>
<p><strong>CO-OCCURRING CONDITIONS:</strong> 1. <strong>Autism Spectrum
Disorder:</strong> Diagnosed September 1, 2025 2. <strong>Generalized
Anxiety Disorder:</strong> Present 3. <strong>Major Depressive
Disorder:</strong> Recurrent, Moderate</p>
<p><strong>INTERACTION EFFECTS:</strong> - ADHD symptoms are exacerbated
by anxiety - Executive function deficits are compounded by ASD -
Treatment requires integrated approach - Phenix Navigator addresses
multiple diagnostic needs</p>
<h2 id="document-5-ada-eligibility-determination">DOCUMENT 5: ADA
ELIGIBILITY DETERMINATION</h2>
<p><strong>ADA ELIGIBILITY CRITERIA MET:</strong></p>
<ol type="1">
<li><strong>Physical or Mental Impairment:</strong> ADHD is a recognized
neurodevelopmental disorder</li>
<li><strong>Substantial Limitation:</strong> Mr. Johnson’s executive
function challenges are rated “Highly Elevated” across all domains,
substantially limiting major life activities including:
<ul>
<li>Learning and concentrating</li>
<li>Thinking and communicating</li>
<li>Performing manual tasks</li>
<li>Working</li>
</ul></li>
<li><strong>Record of Impairment:</strong> Documented diagnosis with
comprehensive psychological evaluation</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>REASONABLE ACCOMMODATIONS REQUIRED:</strong> - Extended time
for processing and decision-making - Written communication preference -
Structured routines and clear expectations - Access to assistive
technology (Phenix Navigator) - Reduced distraction environment - Task
breakdown and step-by-step instructions</p>
<h2 id="legal-significance">LEGAL SIGNIFICANCE</h2>
<p>This exhibit establishes:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li><strong>ADA Disability:</strong> ADHD qualifies as a disability
under ADA</li>
<li><strong>Substantial Limitation:</strong> Executive function
impairments substantially limit major life activities</li>
<li><strong>Medical Device Necessity:</strong> Phenix Navigator is
essential for treatment and daily functioning</li>
<li><strong>Reasonable Accommodation:</strong> System qualifies as
reasonable accommodation under ADA</li>
<li><strong>Comorbidity Impact:</strong> Multiple diagnoses compound
functional limitations</li>
<li><strong>Protected Status:</strong> Medical devices are protected
from interference under federal law</li>
</ol>
